{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14236"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.25,0.1,0.24,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6923"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"2677"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45585"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a brief syncopal episode at home earlier today. She struck her head on the floor but reports no ongoing headache, chest pain, or dyspnoea. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications are metformin and perindopril. She lives independently and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and neurological examinations are unremarkable, and there is no focal injury on head and neck examination. An electrocardiogram shows new-onset atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 130/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is commenced on anticoagulation and metoprolol. During 24 hours of inpatient monitoring after starting these medications, her heart rate decreases to 40/min while she remains in atrial fibrillation. She is asymptomatic during these bradycardic periods, and her blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management, in addition to considering temporary cessation of metoprolol?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insert an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator","Commence transcutaneous pacing","Commence digoxin","Insert a pacemaker","Commence atropine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETachycardia-bradycardia syndrome is a manifestation of sinus node dysfunction in which periods of atrial tachyarrhythmia alternate with inappropriate bradycardia. In people with newly diagnosed atrial fibrillation, rate-limiting medicines such as beta-blockers can unmask underlying sinus node disease. The priority is to allow safe and effective rate control for atrial fibrillation while preventing clinically important bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einsert a pacemaker\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient had syncope at presentation and subsequently developed significant bradycardia (40/min) that limits guideline-recommended rate control therapy. Permanent pacing permits continued use of rate-controlling medicines while protecting against symptomatic or clinically significant bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence digoxin\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate because it is also a rate-limiting agent and can exacerbate bradycardia in sinus node dysfunction. It does not address the underlying problem and may worsen pauses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence transcutaneous pacing\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for acute, unstable, symptomatic bradycardia or high-grade atrioventricular block. This patient is haemodynamically stable and asymptomatic during bradycardia, so temporary external pacing is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsert an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator\u003C/strong\u003E is used for prevention of sudden death from ventricular arrhythmias. There is no evidence of ventricular tachyarrhythmia or reduced ventricular function here, so an implantable defibrillator is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence atropine\u003C/strong\u003E is used as a short-term measure for symptomatic bradycardia causing haemodynamic instability. As the patient is asymptomatic with a stable blood pressure, there is no indication for atropine in this scenario, and it would not provide a durable solution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tachycardia-bradycardia syndrome is a common manifestation of sick sinus syndrome, often requiring pacemaker insertion.","Beta-blockers can unmask underlying sinus node dysfunction in patients with atrial fibrillation."],"references":["2021 ESC Guidelines on cardiac pacing and cardiac resynchronization therapy: Developed by the Task Force on cardiac pacing and cardiac resynchronization therapy of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC) With the special contribution of the European Heart Rhythm Association (EHRA)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-06T12:10:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-06T12:13:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6923"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112799"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2677"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Tachycardia-bradycardia syndrome","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-07-31T14:46:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-31T14:46:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4953"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cardiovascular Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4961"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4987","links":{"self":"https://app.eme